<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Poached or steamed salmon calls for lighter wines like Sancerre or Grüner Veltliner, while grilled or cedar-plank salmon can handle medium-bodied reds like Côte de Beaune Pinot Noir. The key is matching the wine's body to the intensity of cooking method rather than just the fish itself.</li>

  <li><strong>Embrace Salmon's Natural Oils with High-Acid Wines</strong> - Salmon's rich omega-3 fatty acids require wines with sufficient acidity to cleanse the palate. Look for wines with at least 6-7 grams per liter of acidity, such as Riesling from Mosel or Albariño from Rías Baixas, which cut through the fish's natural richness without overwhelming its delicate flavor.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve White Wines Slightly Warmer Than Usual</strong> - For salmon pairings, serve white wines at 50-52°F instead of the typical 45-48°F. This slightly warmer temperature allows the wine's texture and mid-palate weight to better complement salmon's substantial mouthfeel, particularly effective with barrel-aged Chardonnay or white Rhône blends.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Salmon Wines</strong> - Unlike bold red meat pairings, wines chosen for salmon rarely benefit from extensive aeration. Light reds like Beaujolais or Loire Valley Cabernet Franc should only be decanted 15-20 minutes before serving to preserve their fresh fruit character that complements rather than competes with the salmon.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Pinot Noir Pairings</strong> - When serving Pinot Noir with salmon, use Burgundy bowls rather than Bordeaux glasses. The wider bowl concentrates the wine's delicate red fruit and earthy aromatics, which harmonize beautifully with salmon's subtle minerality, especially with wild Pacific varieties.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon Species When Selecting Wine</strong> - Atlantic salmon's milder flavor pairs well with Provence rosé or Sancerre, while sockeye salmon's more pronounced taste can handle Loire Valley Chinon or even light Burgundy. King salmon's richest flesh calls for more structured wines like Chablis Premier Cru or Willamette Valley Pinot Noir.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Young, Fresh Wines with Salmon Service</strong> - Salmon's delicate proteins break down quickly, and similarly, the wines that pair best should be consumed within 2-3 years of vintage for whites and 3-5 years for light reds. Aged wines often develop secondary characteristics that can overshadow the fish's subtle flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Account for Sauce Pairing Over Fish Preparation</strong> - The wine should ultimately complement the dominant flavors on the plate. Salmon with dill cream sauce demands different wine treatment than salmon with teriyaki glaze. Match Muscadet with herb-based preparations and off-dry Riesling with Asian-inspired glazes, adjusting your selection based on the sauce's intensity and flavor profile.</li>
</ol>







  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with grilled salmon versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops smoky, caramelized flavors that pair beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or robust whites like oaked Chardonnay. Poached salmon retains delicate, clean flavors that are best complemented by lighter wines such as Sauvignon Blanc, unoaked Chardonnay, or Chablis. The cooking method significantly impacts the wine's tannin and acidity requirements.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine with salmon at the same temperature for both red and white wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">No, serving temperatures should vary by wine style. White wines like Chardonnay or Riesling should be served at 45-50°F to preserve their crisp acidity that cuts through salmon's richness. Light reds such as Pinot Noir are best served slightly chilled at 55-60°F, which enhances their fruit character and prevents the tannins from overpowering the fish's delicate texture.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine mistake do people make most often when pairing with cedar plank salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing wines that compete with rather than complement the cedar's aromatic influence. Heavy, oaked wines can clash with the wood flavors, creating a muddled taste experience. Instead, opt for wines with natural earthiness like Oregon Pinot Noir or mineral-driven whites such as Chablis, which harmonize beautifully with cedar's subtle smokiness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is wine with salmon a good pairing for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely – salmon is one of the most forgiving proteins for wine pairing beginners. Its rich, meaty texture and mild flavor work well with both red and white wines, making it nearly impossible to create a truly bad pairing. Start with classic combinations like Pinot Noir or Chardonnay to build confidence, then experiment with more adventurous options like Gewürztraminer or Côtes du Rhône.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">How do salmon preparation sauces affect wine selection?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauces dramatically shift wine pairing requirements by adding new flavor elements. Creamy dill or hollandaise sauces call for wines with higher acidity like Sancerre or Albariño to cut through richness. Teriyaki or soy-based glazes pair excellently with off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer, whose slight sweetness balances the salty-sweet flavors. Always pair with the sauce, not just the salmon.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value wine option for regular salmon dinners?</h3>
